tourBios.exmtStatus: Conditional - Finished 151-200 on 2013-14 PGA TOUR FedExCup Points List
tourBios.carHigh:
2014: Made the cut in half of his 22 PGA TOUR starts, having collected five top-25 finishes along the way. Finished his season shy of the FedExCup Playoffs, ranked 153rd in the standings. Failed to regain exempt status for the 2014-15 PGA TOUR via the Web.com Tour Finals. Had T31 and T34 finishes, plus two missed cuts, in the Finals...Finished T4 at the Puerto Rico Open in March to earn his first top-10 PGA TOUR finish in his seventh career start...Next-best finish was a T16 at the Valero Texas Open in late March.

 2013: Finished the season making 16 cuts in 21 events. Best finish was a runner-up. He posted eight top-25s...Recorded three top-10 finishes, which came in his first seven outings...Was solo fifth at the Brasil Classic in early April. Moved into contention at Sao Paulo GC with an 8-under 63 in the third round. Wound up playing 32 holes Saturday in the weather-plagued event. A 3-under 68 Sunday put him 15-under, four behind winner Benjamin Alvarado...Added a T8 at the rain-shortened Stadion Classic at UGA in early May...Later that month, earned a career-best T2 at the Mexico Championship to move from No. 32 to No. 15 on the money list...Finished off the Regular Season with top-25s in his last three events (T18, T25, T16)...Entered the final Regular Season event, the Cox Classic, 26th on the money list. A T16 in Omaha allowed him to jump four players who missed the cut and get to 22nd on the list, good enough to secure his 2013-14 PGA TOUR card for the first time...Made the cut in three of the four Web.com Tour Finals' events.

 2012: Played his way into conditional status for 2013 with a T5 at final full-field event, the Winn-Dixie Jacksonville Open. Jumped from 118th to 91st on the money list that week...Finished his rookie year on the Web.com Tour with nine cuts made in 21 starts...Best early season finish was a T11 in April at the Stonebrae Classic...Missed six straight cuts from late May to late July then reeled off five straight cuts made in August and September. 2011: Missed the cut at the News Sentinel Open, his first career Web.com Tour start.
tourBios.otherCarHigh: Was state champion in golf at Webb School of Knoxville, was a five-time all-state member and earned all-region honors in basketball...Named to the 2010 Academic All-ACC team.
tourBios.personal: Instructor is Brad Rose...Favorite courses are The Honors Course (Chattanooga, Tenn.) and Pinehurst No. 2...Never travels without his computer...Follows the Atlanta Braves...Watches "Boardwalk Empire" and "It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia"...Enjoys watching Derrick Rose play basketball, and enjoys vacationing at any beach. Notes that he has never been to New York.

tourBios.carHigh:
2015: Finished the Web.com Tour season with 23 starts, one win, a runner-up and a third-place finish among his four top-25s and 13 cuts made. Was 25th in the final priority-ranking order...In his fifth start of the year, opened with 68-64 to share the 36-hole lead at the Chile Classic. Shot 68 on Saturday to fall one back. Four birdies on the front nine Sunday resulted in a 4-under 31. Came up short on the back nine, making eight consecutive pars and a bogey on No. 18 to finish T3...Won for the first time as a professional at the El Bosque Mexico Championship in Leon in mid-April. His 7-under 65 Saturday was the low round of the day, and it propelled him into the 54-hole lead. Started the final day with a one-shot lead over playing partner Kevin Tway and quickly chalked up birdies at Nos. 1 and 5 to establish the lead. Upped it to four strokes with three consecutive birdies starting at No. 10. Holed out for birdie from a difficult lie in a bunker on No. 11, a shot he says he might make once if given 100 tries. Cruised to the win with five consecutive pars to close the round at 17-under 271. Picked up a check for $126,000, which moved him from No. 37 to No. 2 on the money after seven of 21 Regular Season events. Among those leaving messages of congratulations on his phone was Duke basketball coach Mike Krzyzewski. "That was pretty cool," he said...Had just one top-25 (T19 at The Rex Hospital Open) from May through mid-July before jumping into contention at the Stonebrae Classic. Opened with 66-65 and was one back at the halfway point. Moved into a tie for the lead with one round to go with Si Woo Kim and Jamie Lovemark after all three players shot 69. The trio matched scores again Sunday (68) to set up a three-man playoff in which Kim would prevail, recording a birdie on the first extra hole, the par-5 18th at TPC Stonebrae. The runner-up outing bumped him up four spots on the money list, to No. 3...Finished the Regular Season No. 6 in earnings and a ticket back to the PGA TOUR...Best performance in four Web.com Tour Finals' starts was a T48 at the Small Business Connection Championship at River Run in North Carolina.
